219
00:18:30,960 --> 00:18:38,560
Yes. One of my pet peeves is when people are too 
concise and they equate being concise with brief,  

220
00:18:38,560 --> 00:18:45,520
being brief. And being concise is not about 
absolute word count, it's about economy of  

221
00:18:45,520 --> 00:18:51,400
words. It's about the density of the insight 
that you're sharing. And so you can have a 300  

222
00:18:51,400 --> 00:18:58,080
word memo that's meandering and long-winded and 
a thousand word memo that is tight and concise.  

223
00:18:58,080 --> 00:19:04,880
And so not equating concision with briefness 
I think is a really big one to understand. 

224
00:19:04,880 --> 00:19:11,840
The second thing is a lot of advice about being 
concise, I think misses an important point. So  

225
00:19:13,200 --> 00:19:19,840
we've all heard, "Don't bury the lead, cut to the 
chase." Main point, put the main point at the top,  

226
00:19:19,840 --> 00:19:28,400
bottom line up front, right? And all of these 
pithy aphorisms assume that you actually know  

227
00:19:28,400 --> 00:19:34,160
what your core point is. So you can't cut to 
the chase unless you know what the chase is.  

228
00:19:34,160 --> 00:19:41,120
You can't unbury the lead unless you know 
what the lead is. And so that I found is  

229
00:19:41,120 --> 00:19:46,160
the bottleneck to being concise. It's actually 
not really being clear of what you are thinking,  

230
00:19:46,160 --> 00:19:52,240
that's what's leading to being long-winded.
And you can kind of test this theory because  

231
00:19:52,240 --> 00:19:56,640
most of us have a go-to story that we've told 
a bunch of times, right? We're like, you know  

232
00:19:56,640 --> 00:20:00,320
exactly when people are going to laugh, you know 
when they're going to gasp or hold their breath,  

233
00:20:00,320 --> 00:20:04,720
right? And why are you so good at telling that 
story and why are you so concise about it? Because  

234
00:20:04,720 --> 00:20:10,800
you've told it a bunch of times, you know all 
of the beats. So in meetings though, at work,  

235
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:15,920
we are very rarely talking about the same thing 
that many times it's always something new. It's  

236
00:20:15,920 --> 00:20:20,400
something that we are also probably likely 
processing ourselves and are in the midst  

237
00:20:20,400 --> 00:20:24,880
of processing as we are in a quick turnaround 
time, telling someone else about it, telling our  

238
00:20:24,880 --> 00:20:30,400
team about it. And so you are basically asking 
your brain to do a lot of different processes,  

239
00:20:30,400 --> 00:20:35,120
especially in a real time conversation. You're 
listening to the other person absorbing,  

240
00:20:35,120 --> 00:20:39,040
making sense of it, processing it, figuring 
out what you think and how you would react. 

241
00:20:39,040 --> 00:20:46,080
And then trying to say something cohesive 
that makes sense, right? And then trying to be  

242
00:20:46,080 --> 00:20:50,800
concise about it. So it's just a lot 
of different processes. And so the  

243
00:20:50,800 --> 00:20:56,560
only solution I found consistently 
to being concise is preparation.  

244
00:20:57,200 --> 00:21:03,520
It's not a very glamorous solution by any means, 
but the clearer I am going into a meeting,  

245
00:21:03,520 --> 00:21:09,600
going into a conversation, going into a pitch, 
the better I am at being concise and being able to  

246
00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:15,280
bring the conversation back to the most important 
points at being able to stay flexible, but also  

247
00:21:15,280 --> 00:21:22,960
firm and preparation. I don't mean spending hours 
and hours preparing for a weekly meeting, even a  

248
00:21:22,960 --> 00:21:28,240
couple of minutes really makes a huge difference.
Most of us are so back to back in meetings that  

249
00:21:28,240 --> 00:21:32,240
